## Summary

The browser back button doesn't work within the app - it navigates away from the app entirely instead of going back to the previous view/state.

## Scope (Clarified)

### Creates history entry:
- âœ… Feed selection
- âœ… Category selection
- âœ… Virtual feed selection (All, Fresh, Starred)
- âœ… Opening Settings dialog
- âœ… Opening Subscribe dialog
- âœ… Switching tabs within Settings
- âŒ Article selection (no history)
- âŒ Article-to-article navigation (no history)

### Back button behavior:
- **Dialog open** â†’ Close the dialog
- **Tab within Settings** â†’ Go to previous tab (or close if first tab)
- **Feed/category selected** â†’ Go to previous feed/category selection
- **At root state** â†’ Normal browser back (exit app)

## Implementation

Use History API with pushState/popstate:

```typescript
// Navigation state shape
interface NavState {
  type: 'feed' | 'category' | 'virtual' | 'dialog'
  id?: number
  dialog?: 'settings' | 'subscribe'
  settingsTab?: string
}

// On feed selection
function selectFeed(feedId: number) {
  history.pushState({ type: 'feed', id: feedId }, '')
  setSelectedFeedId(feedId)
}

// On dialog open
function openSettings() {
  history.pushState({ type: 'dialog', dialog: 'settings' }, '')
  setShowSettings(true)
}

// On settings tab change
function changeSettingsTab(tab: string) {
  history.pushState({ type: 'dialog', dialog: 'settings', settingsTab: tab }, '')
  setActiveTab(tab)
}

// Handle back button
useEffect(() => {
  const handlePopState = (event: PopStateEvent) => {
    const state = event.state as NavState | null

    if (!state) {
      // At root - reset to initial state
      setSelectedFeedId(null)
      setShowSettings(false)
      return
    }

    // Close any open dialogs first
    setShowSettings(state.dialog === 'settings')
    setShowSubscribe(state.dialog === 'subscribe')

    // Restore navigation state
    if (state.type === 'feed') {
      setSelectedFeedId(state.id)
    } else if (state.type === 'category') {
      setSelectedCategoryId(state.id)
    }
    // etc.
  }

  window.addEventListener('popstate', handlePopState)
  return () => window.removeEventListener('popstate', handlePopState)
}, [])
```

## URL Visibility

Not required - URL can stay as `/`. This is purely for back button behavior, not deep linking.

## Files to Modify

- `app/javascript/application.tsx` - Add popstate listener, wrap navigation in pushState
- `app/javascript/components/SettingsDialog.tsx` - Push state on tab changes
- `app/javascript/components/SubscribeFeedDialog.tsx` - Push state on open

## Edge Cases

- Multiple dialogs (open Settings, then somehow open Subscribe)
- Rapid back button presses
- Back when already at initial state
- Refresh mid-navigation (loses state, that's ok - deep linking is separate)

## Related

- ttrb-175: Deep linking and URL routing system (separate, for later)

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Selecting feed pushes history state
- [ ] Selecting category pushes history state
- [ ] Opening Settings pushes history state
- [ ] Opening Subscribe pushes history state
- [ ] Changing Settings tab pushes history state
- [ ] Back button closes open dialog
- [ ] Back button returns to previous feed/category
- [ ] Multiple backs work correctly
- [ ] At root state, back exits app normally

## Summary

Add vim-style page scrolling shortcuts for the entry content pane:
- **Ctrl+F**: Page down (scroll forward)
- **Ctrl+B**: Page back (scroll backward)

## Context

The entry content pane (right side) can contain long articles. Currently users must use mouse/trackpad to scroll. Keyboard-first users need a way to page through content without leaving the keyboard.

## Vim Convention Reference

- `Ctrl+F` - Forward one page (screen height)
- `Ctrl+B` - Back one page
- (Optional future: `Ctrl+D`/`Ctrl+U` - half page down/up)

## Implementation Approach

### 1. Add ref to ScrollArea viewport in EntryContent

The Radix ScrollArea viewport needs to be accessible for programmatic scrolling:

```tsx
// EntryContent.tsx
const scrollViewportRef = useRef<HTMLDivElement>(null)

// Need to expose ref through ScrollArea or access via DOM
```

### 2. Create scroll handlers

```tsx
const handlePageDown = useCallback(() => {
  if (scrollViewportRef.current) {
    const viewport = scrollViewportRef.current
    viewport.scrollBy({ top: viewport.clientHeight * 0.9, behavior: 'smooth' })
  }
}, [])

const handlePageUp = useCallback(() => {
  if (scrollViewportRef.current) {
    const viewport = scrollViewportRef.current
    viewport.scrollBy({ top: -viewport.clientHeight * 0.9, behavior: 'smooth' })
  }
}, [])
```

Note: Using 90% of viewport height leaves some overlap for reading context.

### 3. Add keyboard commands in application.tsx

```tsx
// Add to keyboardCommands array
{ 
  key: "f", 
  handler: handleContentPageDown, 
  description: "Page down content",
  modifiers: { ctrl: true }
},
{ 
  key: "b", 
  handler: handleContentPageUp, 
  description: "Page up content",
  modifiers: { ctrl: true }
},
```

### 4. Modify ScrollArea to expose viewport ref

Option A: Forward ref through ScrollArea component
```tsx
// scroll-area.tsx
const ScrollArea = React.forwardRef<HTMLDivElement, Props>(
  ({ className, children, ...props }, ref) => {
    return (
      <ScrollAreaPrimitive.Root ...>
        <ScrollAreaPrimitive.Viewport ref={ref} ...>
```

Option B: Use data attribute selector
```tsx
// Find viewport via DOM
const viewport = containerRef.current?.querySelector('[data-slot="scroll-area-viewport"]')
```

### 5. Prevent browser default Ctrl+F (find)

```tsx
// In useKeyboardCommands hook, ensure Ctrl+F is prevented
if (e.ctrlKey && e.key === 'f') {
  e.preventDefault()
  // handle page down
}
```

## Files to Modify

- `app/javascript/components/EntryContent.tsx` - Add scroll ref and expose to parent
- `app/javascript/components/ui/scroll-area.tsx` - Forward ref to viewport
- `app/javascript/application.tsx` - Add Ctrl+F/Ctrl+B to keyboard commands
- `app/javascript/hooks/useKeyboardCommands.ts` - Ensure modifier key support for ctrl
- `app/javascript/components/KeyboardShortcutsDialog.tsx` - Document new shortcuts

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Ctrl+F scrolls content pane down by ~1 page
- [ ] Ctrl+B scrolls content pane up by ~1 page
- [ ] Scrolling is smooth (not jarring)
- [ ] Browser's native Ctrl+F (find) is suppressed when content pane is focused
- [ ] Shortcuts appear in keyboard shortcuts help dialog
- [ ] Works when entry content is selected (not in input fields)
